</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="385" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[125,772,1397,2100]" pageId="17" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis box="[155,263,1500,1523]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="385">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: The new genus differs from all other Old World Agelenini by lacking an epigynal fovea (atrium) (
<taxonomicName pageId="17" pageNumber="385" rank="variety" variety="present">
<emphasis box="[743,759,1534,1557]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="385">v.</emphasis>
present
</taxonomicName>
) and the slit-like copulatory openings (
<taxonomicName box="[622,760,1568,1591]" pageId="17" pageNumber="385" rank="variety" variety="copulatory">
<emphasis box="[622,638,1568,1591]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="385">v.</emphasis>
copulatory
</taxonomicName>
openings located in fovea) (
<figureCitation box="[418,509,1603,1625]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[125,156,1431,1450]" captionTargetBox="[126,1461,151,1406]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[126,1461,151,1406]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 14: Epigynes. A Gorbiscape gorbachevi sp. n., intact, ventral view; B same, macerated, dorsal view; C, D same, posterior views; E, F Asiascape parthica sp. n., intact, ventral views; G same, macerated, dorsal view; H same, posterior view; I Persilena sengleti sp. n., posterior view; D same, intact, ventral view; K same, antero-ventral view; L same, dorsal view. Scale bars = 0.2 mm. Abbreviation: Cd = copulatory duct." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3925245" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3925245/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="385">Figs. 14</figureCitation>
Iâ€“L).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[155,492,1636,1659]" pageId="17" pageNumber="385" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="17.[125,772,1397,2100]" box="[155,492,1636,1659]" pageId="17" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis box="[155,281,1636,1659]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="385">Description</emphasis>
: As for the species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="385" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="17.[125,772,1397,2100]" pageId="17" pageNumber="385">
<emphasis box="[155,248,1668,1692]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="385">Remarks</emphasis>
: Even though, according to the standards currently considered in the modern spider taxonomy, it is not advisable to describe new genera solely on the basis of the female sex, due to the peculiar lack of a fovea on the epigyne, a character so distinct that disabled us from assigning the species to any other genera (even tentatively), we place this species in a separate, monotypic genus. Of course, more spider sampling in Central Asia and the Middle East is desirable, but unfortunately this has long been (and still is) difficult due to political issues, and there is a chance that this species (and especially, its male) will not be collected in near future, if ever.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
